    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: global thresholds -> metric scan (P95/P5) -> trace analysis -> focused metric re-check (P90/P10). Results so far:\n- Metric-level P95/P5 scan found no global-threshold breaches in the incident window across the whole system.\n- Trace analysis revealed a concentrated incident at 2020-05-31 04:21:00 +08:00 with very large latency spikes on docker_004 (trace.self.local.duration_p95 max≈54.667s vs global_p95≈1.173s) and elevated error rates and latency on os_021 at the same timestamp. Several row_count drops between containers are correlated at 04:21.\n- Relaxing to P90/P10 found some container-level signals: docker_004 shows a CPU usage breach (max 50% > global_p90 45%, first seen at 04:00 in-window) while os_021 shows minor disk/write and many equality-edge flags. However, docker_004’s extremely large trace latency at 04:21 (>>50% deviation) makes it the strongest candidate at the container level, and os_021 also shows high trace error/latency at 04:21 (node-level). According to localization rules, the most significant deviation determines the level — traces indicate docker_004 (container) exhibits the largest deviation, but we must confirm resource evidence (CPU, disk, network) near the critical time to infer the underlying reason.\nWhat we can derive so far: the incident is concentrated at ~2020-05-31 04:21:00 +08:00; docker_004 is the top faulty container by trace severity; os_021 (host) also shows faults in traces at the same time. Metrics so far are mixed: docker_004 had earlier CPU spikes and os_021 has disk/write equality-edge flags. We cannot yet conclusively state the root cause reason (CPU, network delay/loss, disk I/O, DB connection issues) without inspecting resource KPI values around 04:21. Next step is to fetch targeted metric values in a tight time window around 04:21 for docker_004 and os_021 to see which resource shows a clear spike or drop coinciding with the trace fault (particularly CPU, disk I/O, network throughput/ICMP, and memory).",
